WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Iceland can be harsh like a lunar landscape.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
But it can also be vivid and green.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I have these moments when I'm biking to work and it's dark.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
And I can see the stars and I can see the moon.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
A harsh winter and a long night can also be beautiful.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And when the summer finally arrives, it brings out the joy.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
And you really reconnect to people who live here again.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
A really close-knit community.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
And being a part of that matters to me.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Sorry, can you just introduce yourself?

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Yes, my name is Olli Pátl Geysan and I serve as the Chief Data Officer at the city of Reykjavík.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
The data scientist finds the story in the data.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
When I started here, I felt like it was a clean slate.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Our mission was to build something.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
We know that digital transformation is ahead.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
We need to evolve with society.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:37.000
How can we, as a city, use data and data analytics to help people?

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.000
To have them accessible on the web.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
To put down these barriers, these walls.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
To improve the quality of life for the residents of Reykjavík.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
So your work means something to somebody.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Our role here as Data Science Office is to bring value from data to our stakeholders within the city of Reykjavík.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
The stakeholders could be the Department of School and Leisure.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
It could be the Department of Welfare, Urban Planning or the City Council or the residents.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
It's almost like going through the phone book or something like that.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.000
But you have to go there, talk to them, listen and do it again and again and again.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
We are just right outside the Arctic Circle.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So during the winter it gets dark and it's obviously cold in Iceland.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:51.000
So the first thing you kind of get to know about Icelanders is that they are crazy about their swimming pools.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
It's ingrained in our culture.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
You know, when you have family photos you maybe go to the countryside and take photos.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:06.000
But my brother, for instance, got a photographer to meet them up at the swimming pool because that's where they were every day, essentially.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:13.000
So his family photos, you know, them standing by the swimming pool, you know, they are crazy.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I got frequent requests, even phone calls, on why can't I see how many guests are in the swimming pools right now.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.000
I need to know this.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.000
And also, like, why can't I just predict how many guests are in the swimming pools right now.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.000
I mean, it's just crazy.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:31.000
It's crazy.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:33.000
It's crazy.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.000
It's crazy.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.000
It's crazy.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:39.000
It's crazy.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:40.000
I need to know this.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:49.000
And also, like, why can't I just predict how many people are going to be in the pools for the next hour or so, two hours, or in different swimming pools.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And what we'd like to do is show the percentage, the capacity of the swimming pool.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Like, Laugardalslaug, which is one of the cool swimming pools here, is at 50% right now.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
And we predict it's going to be at 70% in an hour and 35% in two hours.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So we started looking into this and this became a project on our side with the Department of Sports and Leisure.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
But when we started to dive into it, we saw that, hey, this is going to be a bit complicated.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
I should be looking at you and not the camera?

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Shall we start now?

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Talking to you.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Who the heck are you?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.000
If I knew. No, I'm kidding.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
My name is Inga Rós Gunnarsdóttir.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:35.000
My name is Linnur Halkimsson.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:37.000
My name is Sýri Rerla.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
My name is Þorbjörn Þoranarsson.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:41.000
I'm a senior data scientist.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.000
I am a data scientist.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:45.000
A project manager for Reykjavík City.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Reykjavík.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:49.000
The city of Reykjavík.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.000
My role is modelling, advanced analytics and predictive modelling.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Yeah, that's me, I guess.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Finding meaning or value in something that looks like chaos at first.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And finding a meaningful and beautiful way to present it.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
To put a structure on the data team's work.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
How to break it down and help them keep their deadlines.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Nothing ever happens too quickly for me.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
We have, like, different backgrounds and different skill sets within the team.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Þor is an amazing, you know, machine learning guru.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
But he's also, like, he has this, you know, eye for detail.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And, you know, there's something of an artist about him.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Náttlinnur is...

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.000
He's a great programmer.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
And what happens when your team ignores your deadlines?

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:42.000
They never do.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:50.000
We have these gates.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And it counts how many guests are arriving to the pool.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
We can say, OK, this is just a cumulative sum of people that have gone swimming today.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.000
That's a bit of a pickle.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Because we really don't want to know how many people have been counted in.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Hey, there are 10,000 people at the pool.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Like, that makes no sense.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Can we fix that?

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Without buying new gates.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:13.000
So, changing the protocol.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:15.000
Turned out that...

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.000
We have historical data for in and out of the gates.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:22.000
For one swimming pool in Iceland.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:24.000
The largest swimming pool.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Because there you have these bracelets that you need to hand in when you go out.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
So, we contacted the hardware provider.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And they provided us with historical data.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
And the data is corrected with respect to these bracelets afterward.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
So, we have the data on how long they're staying.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.000
There is a distributional property that we can extract out of it.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
But to make things a little bit more complicated.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
If there's a queue of people trying to leave the swimming pool.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
The people who work at the swimming pool are kind enough to...

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Like, OK, we'll just open the gates for you.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
You don't have to use your card to leave.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
But that's wonderful for everybody, except for the data people.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
Because that ruins our data, essentially.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
But we look at it like it's a good thing.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Or we look at it like it's the kindness of man ruining our perfect structured data.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So, we have to account for that discrepancy.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Our model is a very simple one.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
It's a linear spline model.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.000
And the only inputs are...

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:39.000
Time of the day.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:40.000
Day of the week.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:41.000
And time of the year.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:48.000
Every five minutes we have a process in WebMethods that reads data from the swimming pool gates.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And stores them in our data lake.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
We then use the pins package.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
We get pinned linear models from our Studio Connect.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And we then predict the duration.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
Then we pin that results table in our Studio Connect.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
And that's what our Shiny app accesses.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So, before launching it, it had to go through testing.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
To make sure that this is grounded in reality.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
Because we are not swimming pool executives.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:25.000
We don't really know these numbers.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
We set up a separate Shiny app for the managers of the swimming pools.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
So, going through the testing, it matters to it to go fast.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:35.000
To quickly deliver quickly.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:37.000
And in a way that they understand.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
To show them the numbers.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
Show them the time series.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:43.000
And preferably live.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:45.000
So, it's just like an interactive ggplot.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.000
So, you just hover over.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:49.000
Like, this is the time now.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:51.000
It's half past twelve.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:53.000
The app says that there are fifty people here.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.000
Let's do a count.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:57.000
The feedback was...

00:08:58.000 --> 00:08:59.000
It's essentially ten minutes later.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.000
Everything is spot on.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:03.000
And we thought, okay, is there something we need to improve?

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:05.000
And they said, no, this is fine.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.000
Because that's maybe how long it takes for you to walk there.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:09.000
Or bike.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Or ride your car there.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
When we launched it, it was immediately well received by the residents of Reykjavik.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:26.000
Like, a lot of how we are able to get things off the ground quickly.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Has to do with R and RStudio Connect.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
So, when you do it often enough, you have kind of...

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.000
You have all the tools.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And you just have to pick and choose what works best.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.000
We are the people that actually work with the data.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
But now we're also the people that can deploy this and schedule it.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And, you know, put up a shiny app in production within a week.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:55.000
All the process of transforming and building up these analytical tables of products.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And publishing it.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:05.000
The data science team, if it can do all of that inside one domain, they become superheroes.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
They can do everything.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:18.000
I think I do what I do not only because I love coding and making beautiful things.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:28.000
But also because I believe that working at the city of Reykjavik, I can improve people's lives.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
If only a small bit.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
Making a difference.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:36.000
And maybe it's small.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:43.000
At least it's making an impact which hopefully ends with the citizens.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And making life better for them.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:56.000
If you want to make changes, if you want to matter, then you need to embrace the fact it's going to be challenging.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
You have to just know it's going to be alright.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.000
That's something that I didn't quite realize the magnitude of it before I started.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
But that's a ride worth taking.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
Because through the experience, you grow.

